===from:zayira jordan
===email:zayiraj@hotmail.com
===date:Mon Jun  5 20:34:10 2000
===subject:bio 109 hwk 2
===message:Although allegations of selfishness can be made, the situation regarding a possible giveaway of surplus grain to countries that can't afford buying it is not a simple matter.   In many cases, the political conditions prevent the people in need in those countries of receiving this gift.  Then, in the case that this effort is really well-intentioned the United States would need to allocate the grain as well as develop and oversee the distribution process.  In my opinion, good intentions are not enough sometimes.  These may have to be accompanied by an operating procedure that facilitates the final goal to be achieved.<BR>
<BR>
In terms of the possibility of becoming vegetarians, I would suggest that this type of measure seems unattainable.  A more subtle one could be to limit (by legislation) the amount of grazing lands.  This could also have a positive effect in the global warming because of the known consequences of methane produced by cows.  Again, the depletion of rain forests such as the Amazon (Earth's lung) should be severely restricted.  It makes perfect sense if we look at the long range, since this lands will not be productive for long, but instead will be salted in short and of no more use.<BR>
<BR>
The point should be to take a look at solutions in the long range, but attainable ones.  It is undeniable that many smalls well thought measures could be taken with no large political consequences, whereas some radical ones (as all of US becoming vegies) are not realistic.
=========yorg=========
===from:Katie Ruchti
===email:ktsr1@hotmail.com
