===subject:Biology 109
===message:Proposal #1

In many ways I feel that we should give away surplus grain to help feed those from countries who are in need or cannot afford it to buy it from us.  If we have more than enough of the grain we need, it seems cruel that we would not share it with those countries that are less fortunate than we are.  By assisting other countries, we are helping to save lives.  The fact that 40,000 children under 5 die each day from malnutrition and infection should be motivation enough to help other countries.  Also, one unit of grain can feed 10 people if eaten directly.  This proves that by sharing the additional resources we have with others, we can save lives and help to prevent hunger.
The only objection I have to this is that there are starving children in the United States who could benefit from the surplus of grain.  In many ways I feel that the needs of those in our own country should be met before we offer complete assistance to other countries.  This may sound cruel, but we could put that grain to use in the United States also.  I suppose though that the bottom line is that we should help those who are in need.  If I lived in a country where we needed grain or other items, I too would hope that another country would come to our aide and help as best they could.  Sometimes you have to put yourself in another person's place to really understand.

Proposal #2

This sounds like a justifiable solution to hunger and other problems, but it would be a hard task to achieve.  It sounds wonderful that if we all became vegetarians an additional 250 million people in the world could be fed. This is great but Americans consume a great deal of meat products and it would be hard to change.  Further more, meat provides us with protein and other important nutrients that have nutritional value in our diets.  I realize that there are many vegetarians out there, but I feel that cutting out all meat consumption may prove to be a health risk for many people who depend on meat for protein in their daily diet.  I would totally agree with wanting to cut back on the production and consumption of meat, but cutting it out completely and becoming a nation of vegetarians seems somewhat extreme. I feel that there are other ways that we can help feed the hungry.  It is difficult though to know what the best way is to help aid those in need and how many people would actually comply to become vegetarians in order to help others.  If it would mean that lives could be saved, I would do it. But to get 260 million people to agree would be a definite miracle.
=========yorg=========
