===from:Jill Geer
===date:Fri Jul  7 10:11:20 2000
===subject:Homework #2
===message:Proposal 1:  We (the U.S government) should give away surplus grain to those countries that can't afford to buy it from us. 
<BR>
<BR>
I disagree with this idea.  Giving grain to countries in need will solve immediate hunger problems; however, this plan lacks the ability to solve all problems for an extended amount of time.  First, this plan will cause other countries to become more dependent on the U.S. for food supplies.  Which is fine for awhile, but what happens once our surplus supplies are extinquished?  The reason why we have a surplus is because our entire population is not consuming it all.  If our population is increased by the number of people in another country, this will change our carrying capacity.  I strongly believe that once the surplus is used, the U.S. will strive to feed the people in our country before the people in another one.  The less fortunate country will now be in the same situation it was before the U.S. attempted to solve its hunger problems.  Second, this plan could also lead the country to be dependent on the U.S. in other aspects which would cause a financial burden on the U.S.  
<BR>
<BR>
Proposal 2:  We should all become vegetarians to help feed the hungry people in the world and reduce the environmental effects of livestock production.
<BR>
<BR>
I also disagree with this proposal.  First of all, this proposal is assuming that all the hungry people in the world would eat the meat that the U.S. vegetarians are giving up.  In some malnurished areas of the world, due to the different cultural or religious beliefs, people do not eat meat.  People might say that these people who do not believe in eating meat will help feed others in the world.  Which is fine, but there would still be the problem of those people being malnurished.  Another problem to this proposal is that many people would lose their jobs if the U.S. were to become complete vegetarians.  Then the government would have to find a way to sustain these people.  Also, enforcing this law would be difficult and would raise government expenditures if they where to hire a special "meat police."  I believe that it should be everyone's choice as to what kind of foods they would like to eat.  However, if the U.S. wants to attempt to cut back on meat consumption in our country, they should try raising meat prices.  This would either lead to less people consuming meat, ultimately freeing up meat for other countries, or this would lead to the government having more money to be able to find ways to help these countries in need.  Either way, the U.S. would still be giving people the right to choose their own lifestyles, and be able to help countries in need.
=========yorg=========
