===from:Heather Patterson
===date:Mon Jul 10 22:18:33 2000
===subject:Homework 2
===message:I would first like to comment on proposal 1:<BR> 
<BR>
Ideally, this is a great proposal, but I am concerned about a few things. How will the US ship the food to these other countries and who will pay for it? This is a minor detail, but it must be addressed. Will big companies finance this venture in efforts to be more PC? Or will US taxpayers be forced to fork over more money to Uncle Sam?<BR> 
<BR>
Once the grain arrives to these countries, noone knows if it will be spread about equally for all hungry people to enjoy or if the wealthy or government officials will simply take more than their fair share? Many of these countries that have problems paying for the food to begin with have many more deep-rooted problems than just a food shortage or lack of funding to finance the purchase of food from other countries. Their governments are corrupt and unregulated, not all members of their countries have equal and/or fair rights, the people lack sanitary living conditions--the list could go on forever. The problem is so much deeper than just sending them surplus food. <BR>
<BR>
We, as the United States, need to first help them solve some of their other problems. Many of these countries are over-populated because of lack of education about birth control and the unjust treatment of women. If all these people were simply "fed" the problem would only continue with even more people having 15 kids and 5 wives, children dying before they were 10 and very unsanitary living conditions. The problem is much larger than just sending food, which I completely agree that we should do, but we should also teach these people self-respect and the value of education. When these people are educated, they can go so many more places and do so much more for the countries in which they live.<BR>
<BR>
In regards to proposal 2:<BR> 
<BR>
Again, ideally this is great, but many people, especially Iowans, would NEVER give up their love for red meat. I agree that Americans should eat LESS, as we are becoming a HUGE society in every sense of the word. However, it is unrealistic to expect every American to give up meat for good. <BR>
<BR>
I think that we eat too much meat in the United States as well as too much fatty food. If the government could somehow start a campaign/program promoting a change in diet, I think that the number of vegetarians would increase and the rate of livestock production would decrease. Sadly, we are in a rut of being a "meat and potatos" society but it would really benefit everyone if we could change that. Americans are fat and unhealthy and if we just reduced the amount of meats we ate, not only would we be helping oursleves become more healthy, we would also be lowering the rate of livestock production. More farmers would start producing grain and we would be able to feed MORE people with the grain that we ate than the grain that fed the animals that we eventually would eat. This extra grain that we produced from our slowing livestock production could be sent abroad to help the undernourished.<BR>
<BR>
Another benefit to more vegetarians in the US would be the reduced amount of pollution caused by the livestock. Our water would be more sanitary and the air would be more "pleasant" to breathe. There are several benefits to a world filled with vegetarians, but we are far from that day in time. If every person even vowed to reduced the amount of meat in which they ate and tried to eat healthier, the livestock production would surely decrease and all those corporations would begin to meet the "new" needs of the American people. If the demand for a vegetarian lifestyle became greater, more people would jump on the bandwagon and eat less meat.
=========yorg=========
===from:Emily Gries
===email:bem30@hotmail.com
===date:Tue Jul 11 11:53:17 2000
===subject:homework #2
===message:Proposal # 1 is a tricky idea to contemplate.  One would think a good person's first reaction to it would be yes, of course the U.S. should share its surplus good to help countries in need.  However, when really weighing the pro's and cons of the issue, it can be debated either way with pretty valid support.  On one hand, it is true that our nation is way more economically advanced that most other nations, and we do live "high on the hog" as far as food consumption goes overall. It seems that giving our extra grain to countries in need would be the only humane way of justifying our nation's wealthy position in some ways.  But there are a lot of politics that come in beyond the kind act of sharing when it involves an overseas relationship.  What about shipping costs to get the grain to other nations?  We all know that fuel is extremely expensive right now, so that's an added cost to think about that the national budget may not have room for unless some senators are willing to make some changes!  Also, if you can think of giving food to other countries as analagous to the military operations the U.S. provides, it is easy to see a trend that develops--once the U.S. makes an agreement to help less fortunate nations with military support, or food in this case, this is something which that nation's population will depend on to keep a steady birth and life rate going--and if the U.S. gets to a point where it is too expensive to continue, that nation's population is going to undergo even worse tragedy than before--like giving a bottle to a baby and then taking it away--that baby is going to be upset, because he depended on that nourishment.  So overall, despite my argument here, I really do think the U.S. should be spending a lot more of our national budget to ship surplus food to countries in need,because it seems silly that we fork out billions of dollars to do peace-keeping operations in Kosovo, but can't help peaceful nations with food.  But, as I made the point earlier, there are a lot of tricky twists that can come out of sharing, depite the virtue of it, and these risks might be over the limit of what the U.S. can handle in order to keep our nation strong at the same time.

     As far as proposal #2 goes, it's a nice idea, but I think it's just too extreme to ever work--no one would stand for that--it would have to be a law in order to get the majority of U.S. citizens to follow it, and then it could be argued that a law outlawing meat-eating is unjust, inhumane, a deprivation of human rights, or something similar.  Plus, it can't be ignored that a vegetarian diet, although very healthy if done correctly, can deprive the body of the protein needed to make hemoglobin and and that other anatomy stuff that I really don't know much about.  If the nation all of the sudden went to a strictly vegetarian diet, there would be a lot of sick people, a sudden death rate increase perhaps, and a lot of pissed off people.  It is a nice idea, as I said before, but a lot of nice ideas just don't work in a democracy.  So unless we wnat to change our nation's political basis and re-do the revolutionary war to declare us NOT a democracy, then this idea is sadly, just not going to fly with the majority of U.S. citizens.  That's all I have to say.  Good-bye.

=========yorg=========
