===message:Proposal #1
   Perhaps if there is a surplus of grain in the United States, it would be beneficial to developing nations to provide them not only with the abundant grain but also with agricultural planners who could help the starving communities develop sustainable agricultural practices.  I fear that only sending the grain may breed dependency instead of self-sufficency in areas of the world where political and economic troubles prevent humans from living a prosperous, healthy existance.  Another factor to consider in sending such aid is the political state of the country and whether or not the people in need will actually receive any of the much needed food.  In the end, any attempt to feed the starving people of the world is better than allowing grain to rot in the bins of US farmers.

Proposal #2
     What a wonderful day when more people accept vegetarism as a viable alternative to a traditional meat-based diet.  I think it would be a great idea for more better to consume alittle lower on the food chain so that others may eat as well.  Yet, I feel that if all the citizens of the United States where to stop eating meat, we would have devastating economic and agricultural problems.  For one, unless measures were taken to transform the meat industary into say a soy industry, a large surge of unemployment would result as farmers of livestock lose their niche in the community.  Also, what would the world do with all the cows, chickens, and pigs that have been engineered to have little purpose other than to eat and reproduce.  A sudden overpopulation of livestock would destroy the land by overgrazing.  Eventually, a massive slaughter/bonfire would need to take place to eradicate the "livestock pests," so wouldn't it be more beneficial if a few people in the US just continued to eat meat, even if only on occasion.  Perhaps the most logical plan involves a moderate balance between carnivores and herbivores.  I believe it would be wonderful if a majority of people gave up meat to feed the world, but I think meat-eaters have their place on the food chain as well.
